segments.text: Who were the playmates that were numerous enough for you to play a baseball game or basketball?
Well, on the block that we lived on, there were two duplices that were reserved, I guess, for the military people.
And from time to time, there were, I can remember three.
families that lived next door to us in one of the duplexes that all had two or three children.
There was Captain Lines and Major Stickney and Captain Marcus and all of them, they all had children.
And they'd be there three, four, five years and then the military would be transferred.
But some of the ones that were raised
There was Brooks Colfer, who lived down the street.
John Sandstedt, Dillard Spriggs, and Joe Orr.
All of them were the sons and daughters of faculty members.
In terms of the social status on the campus, was there any part of the campus where
there was greater prestige of living here than living there?
Well, I suppose, looking back on it, there was, but it never occurred to me that we weren't as good or as bad as anybody else, you know?
And we lived in a, I guess the college position would be one of the more prestigious positions, and we lived next door to him, you know?

next on the other side dean marsh steller of dean of the veterinary school and next door to him was dean kyle the head of the dean of the ag the school of agriculture and so you know that we we live right there in that neighborhood uh the president of the college lived uh half a block from us so uh you know and i said i said i suppose there were

I know that most of the men that worked in the building college utilities, the painters, the plumbers, and the carpenters, and the people that ran the power plant and all, lived in the area near the power plant, but it didn't occur to me that that was any, a blue collar area, but
looking back on it, they lived over there because that's where they were.
Where they lived in the area of the BNCE department.
There was an area where Dean Bolton lived and the commandant, whoever happened to be commandant at that time, and the deans of several other areas.
Dr. Gammon, who was
I guess he was the history department chairman.
In those days, I guess they were departments, weren't they?
The history department.
He was the chairman of the history department.
Dr. Liam, I think, was the accountant.
Knox Walker's daddy.
I guess he was Knox Walker, too.
If I'm not mistaken, was in charge of all the
building the engineering for Prairie View and Tarleton.
He lived on the Indian campus.
Did you have a special buddy?
Well, I spent more time with Jack Marsh because he lived next door, and he's a bit older.
That was attractive to me.
Now, where could you and your brother and three or four others, what did you all do, if anything, for mischief?
Well, I remember one time we were going to have a war with all the kids that lived off the campus in College Park.
And we, the marshes had a big, they had an old barn behind the house that had been converted into a garage, but still had a loft.
And we armed the loft with China berries and
all sorts of stuff and waited for them to attack us.
But they didn't, they didn't show up and that afternoon we wound up having a touch football game on the field.
So I guess the war, but we, I don't know, we played cowboys and Indians and cops and robbers.
What were the, were there any in your family
Were there any rules, any forbidden things that y'all were to do on the campus?
Well, we weren't supposed to go in the dormitories.
I remember that on Sunday, if we didn't go to Sunday school and we didn't go to church, we didn't go to free show and we didn't play touch football.
I remember I
At one point, I decided that I wasn't going to Sunday school to church.
I said, okay, stay home.
And when my folks got home that afternoon, or at noon from church, we had lunch, and so I got ready to go to the movie, and they wanted to know where I thought I was going.
I said, I was going to the free show.
They said, you didn't go to Sunday school?
You didn't go to church?
I said, I had no free show for you this afternoon.
No football, and I had a pretty difficult time.
If they didn't have a touch football game on Sunday close to the house, I didn't get to play.
I couldn't go.
There's nearly always a touch football game somewhere around Kyle Field, and on Sunday afternoon I couldn't go.
I remember one time,
I was, when I was a freshman at A&M that first summer, I had walked on, and the football team, we practiced all summer long.
There were, I guess during the war, there were no particular rules about it.
And Coach Norton had put in the T-formation.
That was the first time they'd ever used the T-formation.
Dick Todd, who was an All-American at one time, was playing for the Iowa Seahawks.
And he got a weekend pass and came down to do some special work with us.
And Coach Norton, he was going to be there Friday, Saturday, and Sunday.
And he wanted us to work out on Sunday.
And I had an awful hard time asking my dad.
on Sunday, but he didn't seem to, I don't know whether he minded or not, but he didn't object.
Right now, when you're in junior, senior high, got a bicycle, where would y'all ride off to?
I'd maybe go to Kyle Field.
Because there wasn't a creek anywhere nearby to go swimming or fishing.
Well, we'd
We went fishing in the zoo lake once in a while.
The zoo, do you remember where the creamery used to be?
West of the creamery.
That one time there was a zoo.
They had lions and tigers.
And they had dug out an old U-shaped lake.
And in the U, the YMCA had built a canyon.
In fact, they took three of the shacks
that the students used to live in and put them together in the form of a T. And that was the Y cabin.
The Y cabin.
And it was later, if I'm not mistaken, moved to Hensel Park and named Cashin cabin.
I think it's been remodeled, but it's still named Cashin cabin.
Anyway, there was a lake that had some perch in it and we used to, my dad loved to fish.
And we'd go down there and fish with the cane and pole.
And that was where he had his steak fries for his YMCA cabinet and other student groups.
In today's terms, how diverse was the population that you remember of campus and friends and NM Solid Age students?
Not diverse at all.
So no Hispanics, no blacks?
The blacks were the ones that I knew worked as servants.
Cooks, maids, the main ones that I knew that I knew best worked in the hospital.
Where did they live?
Well behind each house on the campus there was a small one-room house that was made available
to these people.
Most of them live along Weldon Road from Uncle Ed's Beer Joint south till the highway across the railroad track.
There was a whole area
just small houses that primarily black people lived in.
I remember they had a, just a beer jar called the Green Lantern.
And it was about halfway between what's now the corner of Bush Drive and Weldon Road and

The highway used to go on the east side of the railroad down to about where 2818 crosses, and then it crossed over and went on the west side until it got to Welber, and then it crossed back over and went on the east side to Milliken.
And all on that, where the highway was on the east side, were just small houses that were primarily black people.
You mentioned Uncle Ed's.
Was Uncle Ed's there as early as you can remember?
Describe it and what it was and who went there.
I never did go in Uncle Ed's very often, but it was a beer joint.
The nearest thing I think of right now would be a convenience store or an ice house.
They had that little room where you
They had some tables and the guys could get beer there.
I guess in that precinct, they sold beer.
And as far as you know, it was legal.
Yes, it was legal.
It was legal and he had a grocery store and that's where the people that lived down there bought their groceries from Eiffel Head and I'm sure he had some sort of a charge account with them.
Now, was this, was he Herdlicka?
Is it Ed Herdlicka?
Yeah, I will call it Hardlicka.
I don't know.
Okay, that's what I was going to say.
H-R-D-L-C-K-A or something.
So that, because I've heard some people refer to Hardlickers, and so Uncle Ed's is the same.
Now, did people go there, as far as you know, and really get drunk, or did they go and have a beer or two?
Probably both.
Okay.
Probably both.

You know, in the song that was written for the Aggieland Orchestra about I'd rather be a Texas Aggie, one of the phrases in there, we'll go to Uncle Ed's and drink our cares away, that's what they're talking about.
Was, as far as you know, if an Aggie had a date, would it have been acceptable to take the date to Uncle Ed's?
Or was it pretty well a male only?
Well, I'm sure it was pretty well male only, because there were only males on the campus, you know, for the most part.
And I really can't tell you a whole lot about it, because I was, I mean, I didn't go to that kind of place as a child, you know, obviously.
Now, you mentioned another place down the...
The Wilburn Road.
Well, the Green Ladder, but that was the Black Force.
Oh, okay.
That was their beer joint.
Okay.
Was there, there was nothing on the East Gate to speak of, was there?
The East Gate, no, there was no East Gate until they built Highway 6.
But I mean, by World War II.
By World War II, they had that East entrance, yes.
But was there any kind of...
Well, there were, let's see, out on the highway, there were two service stations that I can remember.
The first one was Grant's Gulf Station, and it's on the corner where the Chevron Station is now next to the High Rise Hotel.
It was Grant's Gulf.
Right across the street, there was a Phillips Station.
And down the highway south, just between there and the entrance, there was Black's Pharmacy.
And there was a, there were two services out there, Texaco and Exxon.
I was a homeboy at that time.
And there was a hamburger joint out there called, let's see, what was his name?
I can't remember that now.
It may come to me.
He had just a small building out there about where, you know, somewhere, it was right on the highway, but it was about where Barnes and Noble is, somewhere along in there.
It was just a hamburger joint, a beer joint.
All right, go to Northgate.
What was at Northgate when you were high school, junior, and senior high?
Northgate, there were two drug stores on the corner.
Maidley's Pharmacy and the Aguland Pharmacy.
Wait, at Northgate, Maidley's?
Oh.
No, no, no, no, no.
Not Maidley's.
It was Lipscomb.
I'm sorry.
Lipscomb.
Maidley was at the Southgate.
But the Aguland Pharmacy was the first one.
And it's the photo shop.
Mm-hmm.
And then Dr. Lipscomb may have had a hand in building it.
And then he later built another Lipscomb Pharmacy right across the street.
Where Lupo is.
Right.
Was Lou in business then?
Lou was in business sometime in the 30s.
But there was a little building.
down toward the campus theater.
It was separate, just a little wooden building, separate.
In the block there where the Lipscomb Pharmacy was, behind it, there was, what was the man's name that made uniforms?
I can't remember his name, but then there was the grocery store back there, Luke and Charlie's Grocery Store, and the photo shop, I mean, Hollick's.
Soslick's.
Soslick's Photography was on the farm.
Across the street there was the Hollick's Boot Shop, Lauterstein's Cleaners, and I can't think of the man's name that was the tailor.
But he, one of the things that we all, he tailor-made military slats.
And most of us were pretty pencil thin, and he built, he did, I can't think of what his name was now, but he was there for years and years.
And then the, in terms of the churches, the Baptist and...
The Baptist church was on, were behind,
on the right side, across the street from the Church of Christ.
And then the Methodist Church was behind the Baptist Church.
The Catholic Church was on down the street.
And for the most part, these were separate buildings.
You know, I mean, A.M. Waldrop had a uniform shop there, and a barber was a barber shop next to the Agland Inn, I mean, Agland Pharmacy.
barbershop and then A.M. Walters Uniform and there was a jewelry store next to the barbershop.
Now let's see, let's go back to your high school.
You all had football, organized football team at the high school?
Football, I think the first year was in 1935 or 6.
And who played?
The first game that was ever played was against Willow Hole.
And Willow Hole was a rural school just south of .
The church is still there.
Willow Hole Baptist Church is still there.
And there was a school there.
And the first game that Consolidated ever played was at Senior Field, Willow Hole, and I had a ticket.
Do you remember any discussion as to how the mascot was selected?
They were the Tigers.
One thing that's kind of interesting though, of course the colors were maroon and white,
At one time, the A&M annual was the longhorn, and the annual for the skills was the shorthorn.
And then they changed it to the Aggieland, and they changed the one that consulted it to the Tigerland.
Okay.
Now, were they playing basketball and baseball before football?
No, no.
So that sports...
and see it, and then they had a basketball team, but they didn't have a gym.
And so the only practice that we got was the A&M down by DeWare Field House, there was a wooden gym, they called it the Little Gym.
It had three or four handball courts and a basketball court.
And we practiced in the Little Gym
When we could, but they used it for intraburals and so on, and so sometimes it got to be just on the weekend.
And the basketball season consisted of about eight or ten games, if I'm not wrong.
And football, we also, we played, one year we played marquee for the district championship.
And Marquette had a team, Jewett.
Those two schools are consolidated now, Leon.
And we played Buffalo.
We played, the first game I ever played in was at Dayton, Texas.
We went down to Dayton and played then.
Now with that, were y'all class B?
We were class B and I think at that time there were only maybe two or three classes.
Double A, A and B is all I knew of.
As a Class B school, we only played by district.
The first year I was in high school, the district was divided into two zones.
We won the South Zone.
The South Zone was Consolidated, and Snook, and Beat Eyes, and Owl, and North Zoo.
And in the north end of the zone, there was Jewett, Marquet, Buffalo, and maybe Normandy, I'm not sure.
But anyway, we played Marquet in Bryan at the old Forest Stadium in Bryan.
And Marquet beat us.
And the next year, the next year we played
Buffalo in Madisonville for the district championship.
And we beat Buffalo and played Wortham in the bi-district and they beat us.
And then in the next two years we won bi-district.
Now, where in high school, where did y'all have social events like a senior prom or a... Well, I remember the
We didn't have a prom, but we had a banquets.
Junior senior banquets.
Where would you have that?
My junior year, we had it in the library study hall.
A study hall was probably the size of two classrooms and a library on one end of it.
Oh, in the old high school building.
Okay, on campus.
Right, on campus.
My senior year, they had built a gym, and so we had the junior-senior banquet in the gymnasium.
In the new A&M Salt Lake building off campus?
Well, the gym has been torn down.
No, but I mean it was new then.
Yes, it was new then.
All right.
When you and your buddies wanted to have a social Saturday night in high school, where did you all go?
Generally...
If we didn't go to somebody's house, we went to a movie.
Probably Brian, the Palace Theater, or the Campus Theater, which was open in those days.
And that was primarily the dates.
We'd go to a movie and then, you know, to a drive-in.
or to somebody's house.
We did lots of socializing in people's homes.
Now, as far as you recall, what were the boundaries of adult, talking about your parents now, of adult conduct then for faculty and staff members?
What are the things that they just did not, wouldn't have thought about doing?
Well, let me see.
I don't know.
I guess I can only speak for my own parents.
I never saw them take a drink.
They may have, but there never was any liquor of any sort in our home.
As far as you know, when they went to someone else's, was it similar?
Yes, as far as I know.
That's what I understand.
You know, the kinds of things they did were also in people's homes.
They played lots of dominoes, 42.
Were there any games that just, did they ever play, did they play cards?
Yeah, they played cards.
Bridge?
Bridge, there was bridge and pinochle.
Did anybody ever play any games for money?
If they did, I didn't know.
Okay.
Did they go to, did they go to dances?
Well, I think, if I'm not mistaken, they chaperoned some of the Nazis.
Occasionally, I can remember a time or two, my folks going to some sort of social functions that were more than just visiting somebody's home, but I can't tell you what they did.
Divorce.
I didn't know anybody at the board.
And I didn't know any women that I didn't know any women that smoked.
There was an awful lot of social activity with churches.
The women's circles and that sort of thing were the circle meetings once a month were big social things.
Were there any
allegations as to which church denomination was favored at A&M?
Not that I know of.
They had a big group, you know, and the Presbyterian church was pretty noticeable because they met on the campus.
And as far as I know there was no stigma
to the church, giving preference to one or the other.
And as I recall, but I'm not sure what the procedure was, but at one time, I think they had a chapel.
And the students were required to attend chapel.
But I don't know who ran it.
Now, who was the president of A&M when you were growing up?
Well, Dr. Walton, for the most part, and then Gib Gilchrist.
Describe President Gilchrist, or Dean Gilchrist.
He wasn't first.
Dean Gilchrist, yes.
Well, Dean Gilchrist was quite an imposing figure.
He was tall, and I guess he was pretty stubborn.
one of the things that everybody held against him was he went to the University of Texas.
But he ran things pretty much with an iron fist.
You know the story about his, right after the war, there seemed to be
between the corps and the non-corps, the veterans.

And the corps, I don't remember exactly what it was all about, but the officers were gonna resign and they marched to the president's home and gave him an ultimatum and he said, well, wait a minute, guys.
put a box out there, put all your buttons and diamonds in the box and go back home, go to class.
And he took their resignation, his officers in the Corps stopped the revolt, whatever it was.
And I'm not absolutely sure that what I've said is correct for the record, but I think it's pretty well documented.
Something like that happened.
Of the presidents that your dad dealt with, did he have any favorite that he respected most?
Well, of course, there was some tie.
My mother and Gib Gilchrist's families went back to Willisville.
Oh, that's right.
That's right.
And so I don't suppose there was any favoritism, but from a family standpoint, we were closer to the Gilchrist than we were to the Wildcats.
Because, I mean, my mother and Gibb Gilchrist were... Henry is... Henry's the son.
He's...
I think Henry's two years older than I am.
He was two years ahead of me in consolidation.
Because he has told me, I haven't interviewed him yet, but just in conversation, he said when they moved here, I believe he said he was 13...
and his dad robbed him by buying him a new bicycle.
Oh, really?
And he thought, by comparison with the new house they left in Austin, that he had moved to a little old bitty country town.
And he said at first it was hard for him to get...
I can see why he moved from Austin to College Station.
You'd think he moved to... Well, it probably was a country town.
When...
